Serving as a foundational exercise in digital logic or embedded systems design, this prototype bridges abstract 
circuit schematics with physical hardware-in-the-loop testing. The architecture of the circuit is centered around
three dual in-line package (DIP) integrated circuits (ICs) mounted across the board's central isolation divider. 
These ICs function as the primary logic or signal routing nodes of the system, manipulating electrical states based on 
incoming control signals.
Efficient signal routing and electrical distribution are critical to the system's operation.
Power is distributed uniformly across the entire board via side-mounted positive and negative power rails,
which are cross-connected using small jumper wires to eliminate voltage drops. A dense network of colored jumper
wires handles the logic-level data transmission, interconnecting the various IC pins. Additionally, the circuit
features discrete peripheral components, including a signal diode for directional current control and light-emitting 
diodes (LEDs) positioned at the top to serve as visual state indicators. For a Computer Engineering student, 
fabricating this breadboard assembly highlights essential skills in pinout mapping, power bus management, and hardware 
debugging prior to moving toward a permanent printed circuit board (PCB) layout.
